# .dockerignore — files excluded from the build context sent to
# the Docker daemon. Without this, `COPY . .` would send the
# entire working tree (node_modules/, .git/, pb_data/, *.db, etc.)
# wasting time and leaking data into the build context.
#
# In 2026 this is standard hygiene alongside a multi-stage build.
# See: https://docs.docker.com/build/building/context/#dockerignore-files

# ── VCS ──
.git
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# ── CI / docs / meta ──
.github
docs

# ── Editor / IDE / OS ──.vscode
.idea
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
*.swp
*~

# ── Node (Tailwind + DaisyUI build deps) ──
# node_modules is populated by `npm install` inside the builder.
# Sending the host's node_modules to Docker would 1) waste build
# context time and 2) potentially leak host-specific binaries.
node_modules
npm-debug.log
package-lock.json

# ── Go (test/binary data, build cache) ──
# The builder re-downloads modules into a BuildKit cache; no
# need to send the host's cache.
vendor
*.test
*.out
coverage.txt
*.cover
*.coverprofile

# ── PocketBase runtime data ──
# Test data + production data should never end up in an image.
pb_data
data
internal/workflow/pb_data
features/todo/pb_data
*.db
*.db-shm
*.db-wal

# ── Build artifacts (rebuilt inside the image) ──
bin
tmp
dist
out
*.log

# ── Generated by the build (re-emitted on each build) ──
# If these are committed, exclude them so the build always
# produces fresh ones from the source-of-truth files.
**/*_templ.go
**/app.min.css

# ── The repo's own template files that we DON'T need at build time ──
# `.air.toml` is for `make dev` (host-side). Dockerfile uses
# `go build` directly.
.air.toml

# Reference docs / templates the build doesn't read.
templates
references

# Anything that's not source: HTML, screenshots, plans.
*.html
*.png
*.jpg
*.jpeg
*.gif
*.svg
*.pdf
*.md
!docs/**/*.md
!README.md
!AGENTS.md
!CHANGELOG.md
